1
00:00:06,423 --> 00:00:08,633
[Es]<i> Over the last two decades of working,</i>

2
00:00:08,717 --> 00:00:13,007
<i>one of the things I've discovered</i>
<i>is often things are made to fill voids.</i>

3
00:00:13,096 --> 00:00:14,426
[light switch echoes]

4
00:00:16,099 --> 00:00:19,979
[Es]<i> The impetus to fill that hole</i>
<i>with art, to me, is fundamental.</i>

5
00:00:20,062 --> 00:00:22,152
[other-worldly music playing]

6
00:00:25,234 --> 00:00:28,954
[Es]<i> My canvas tends to be</i>
<i>devoid of light.</i>

7
00:00:31,782 --> 00:00:35,792
<i>You sort of do need to start</i>
<i>without light to find it.</i>

8
00:00:37,621 --> 00:00:39,711
[other-worldly music continues]

9
00:01:47,399 --> 00:01:50,529
[director] Here's my first question,
and I've been curious about this.

10
00:01:50,611 --> 00:01:53,861
Do you pronounce your name
"Ezz" or "Ess"?

11
00:01:53,947 --> 00:01:58,827
I pronounce my name "Ezz,"
because my name is short for Esmeralda.

12
00:01:58,910 --> 00:02:02,210
Often it's perceived
as being a man's name,

13
00:02:02,748 --> 00:02:07,748
so I do get reviews in Germany, which say,
"<i>Herr</i> Devlin's incredibly masculine work

14
00:02:07,836 --> 00:02:11,666
would have benefited from reading
the feminine aspects of the text."

15
00:02:11,757 --> 00:02:14,337
So, it's a useful,
neutral little name, actually, Es.

16
00:02:14,426 --> 00:02:18,256
I find it quite handy.
It's serving me quite well as a name.

17
00:02:26,063 --> 00:02:29,573
Every project starts exactly like this.

18
00:02:29,650 --> 00:02:34,320
Blank piece of paper, blank table,
there's usually one other person there.

19
00:02:34,404 --> 00:02:38,584
<i>Could be a director, or a playwright,</i>
<i>or the artist, if it's for a pop show.</i>

20
00:02:39,159 --> 00:02:40,869
<i>And a conversation happens,</i>

21
00:02:40,952 --> 00:02:43,792
<i>and I'd normally just start drawing</i>
<i>while we're talking.</i>

22
00:02:44,289 --> 00:02:49,669
<i>So, if I were to be having a conversation</i>
<i>about my own practice,</i>

23
00:02:49,753 --> 00:02:52,763
it would start with this one,

24
00:02:52,839 --> 00:02:56,339
with a little drawing
of a pair of scissors on it.

25
00:02:56,426 --> 00:02:59,136
'Cause you used to get those,
and you still do,

26
00:02:59,221 --> 00:03:00,891
on the back of a cornflakes packet,

27
00:03:00,972 --> 00:03:05,812
and it's an invitation to take
the piece of the cornflakes packet

28
00:03:05,894 --> 00:03:07,814
and cut it and make an intervention in it

29
00:03:07,896 --> 00:03:10,146
and change it
and turn it into something else.

30
00:03:12,192 --> 00:03:14,112
Like that, that will do.

31
00:03:14,194 --> 00:03:16,074
And then you hold it up to the light
and you go,

32
00:03:16,154 --> 00:03:18,574
"Oh, there's light
just coming through that bit that I cut!"

33
00:03:19,241 --> 00:03:20,371
So I like that one.

34
00:03:22,202 --> 00:03:25,292
I often get asked by people,
"How did you start doing what you do?"

35
00:03:25,372 --> 00:03:27,872
I often get asked by young,
like, 17-year-old people,

36
00:03:27,958 --> 00:03:29,248
who don't know what to do.

37
00:03:29,334 --> 00:03:33,844
And I always feel very empathetic
towards those 17-year-old people

38
00:03:33,922 --> 00:03:35,172
who say, "I don't know what to do."

39
00:03:36,425 --> 00:03:39,175
<i>I was no different to that,</i>
<i>I didn't know what to do at all.</i>

40
00:03:39,469 --> 00:03:41,849
<i>But then I did a course in theater design</i>

41
00:03:41,930 --> 00:03:45,640
<i>and I found myself in this room full</i>
<i>of people making model stuff.</i>

42
00:03:46,101 --> 00:03:48,271
<i>I thought, "This is good,</i>
<i>these people are feral,</i>

43
00:03:48,353 --> 00:03:51,313
<i>and they stay up all night making models,</i>
<i>I feel quite at home here."</i>

44
00:03:51,398 --> 00:03:54,608
So, I did that.
I just made stuff for a year in this thing

45
00:03:54,693 --> 00:03:57,323
and then at the end of it,
I won this prize.

46
00:04:00,282 --> 00:04:03,242
<i>One of the first major shows</i>
<i>I was asked to do</i>

47
00:04:03,326 --> 00:04:05,826
was the Harold Pinter play<i>, Betrayal.</i>

48
00:04:07,289 --> 00:04:12,459
Big piece at the National Theatre
in London, so I threw everything at it.

49
00:04:13,628 --> 00:04:19,428
<i>And it says it's set in a bedroom,</i>
<i>a living room, a hotel room in Venice,</i>

50
00:04:19,509 --> 00:04:24,469
<i>and what I did is I overlaid</i>
<i>the ground plans of every scene</i>

51
00:04:24,556 --> 00:04:26,096
<i>with projections.</i>

52
00:04:26,725 --> 00:04:31,605
<i>And at that time, it was quite unusual</i>
<i>to use projection and film in theater.</i>

53
00:04:32,189 --> 00:04:34,859
<i>There wasn't really</i>
<i>an infrastructure for it to work.</i>

54
00:04:35,650 --> 00:04:39,700
And the point about that particular play
is it really doesn't need any of that.

55
00:04:39,780 --> 00:04:43,030
It does not need it.
It's a very happy play in a white box

56
00:04:43,116 --> 00:04:46,446
with a few white curtain changes
and furniture, it's happy that way.

57
00:04:46,536 --> 00:04:51,326
But that was me, I was doing my thing
and Harold Pinter was very sweet about it.

58
00:04:51,416 --> 00:04:53,956
'Cause he was quite excited
to see all this gadgetry,

59
00:04:54,044 --> 00:04:59,094
and, as a joke, he, on the first night,
introduced me to Antonia Fraser,

60
00:04:59,174 --> 00:05:01,684
his wife, Lady Antonia Fraser,

61
00:05:01,760 --> 00:05:03,800
and said, "This is Es,
she wrote the play."

62
00:05:04,596 --> 00:05:06,056
So that was sweet.

63
00:05:06,139 --> 00:05:08,139
[futuristic music playing]

64
00:05:09,518 --> 00:05:13,358
<i>The beginnings of my practice</i>
<i>were making small theater.</i>

65
00:05:14,105 --> 00:05:17,525
<i>You know, literally, there's an audience</i>
<i>of 78 at the Bush Theatre,</i>

66
00:05:17,609 --> 00:05:18,939
<i>which was where I first started working.</i>

67
00:05:20,487 --> 00:05:23,867
[Bradwell]<i> The Bush Theatre</i>
<i>is about the size of a matchbox.</i>

68
00:05:24,699 --> 00:05:27,159
What it was, was close-up magic.

69
00:05:27,244 --> 00:05:30,334
We created worlds
in a very, very tiny space.

70
00:05:32,290 --> 00:05:36,380
<i>How do you build a revolve</i>
<i>in a theater that seats 80 people?</i>

71
00:05:36,461 --> 00:05:39,341
<i>How do you do projections,</i>
<i>television screens?</i>

72
00:05:40,131 --> 00:05:42,051
<i>People were spending</i>
<i>a lot of money doing that.</i>

73
00:05:42,133 --> 00:05:45,053
We were spending
about four quid doing it out of junk

74
00:05:45,136 --> 00:05:48,426
and Es was working out how to do it,
every single step of the way.

75
00:05:48,515 --> 00:05:51,175
She'd paint the set,
she'd make the stuff, she'd weld.

76
00:05:53,228 --> 00:05:56,148
[Es]<i> I began to find what I wanted</i>
<i>to say quite quickly</i>

77
00:05:56,231 --> 00:05:57,321
<i>and quite quickly,</i>

78
00:05:57,399 --> 00:06:00,779
people who didn't like the kinds of things
I was doing stopped asking.

79
00:06:04,948 --> 00:06:09,658
<i>My practice has been following</i>
<i>my own paths of inquiry.</i>

80
00:06:11,496 --> 00:06:16,206
<i>And in order to practice,</i>
<i>I have found willing collaborators</i>

81
00:06:16,293 --> 00:06:20,713
<i>who I've been able to align my paths</i>
<i>of inquiry with.</i>

82
00:06:22,048 --> 00:06:28,178
<i>From pop stars like Beyonc√©,</i>
<i>through to Wagner operas.</i>

83
00:06:31,808 --> 00:06:34,848
<i>The interesting thing about the process...</i>

84
00:06:34,936 --> 00:06:39,686
<i>I've learned that I don't actually</i>
<i>make anything or know what to make,</i>

85
00:06:39,774 --> 00:06:43,194
<i>until I know what the space is</i>
<i>that it's going to inhabit.</i>

86
00:06:43,820 --> 00:06:45,030
<i>'Cause as soon as you have a frame,</i>

87
00:06:45,113 --> 00:06:48,243
<i>of course the first thing you want to do</i>
<i>is start breaking out the edge of it.</i>

88
00:06:51,995 --> 00:06:55,325
The Faith Healer<i> is a series of monologues</i>

89
00:06:55,415 --> 00:06:58,415
<i>through rain, through sludge,</i>
<i>through bleakness.</i>

90
00:07:02,297 --> 00:07:06,587
<i>The interstitial gaps</i>
<i>between each monologue</i>

91
00:07:06,676 --> 00:07:11,176
<i>needed to evoke that itinerant bleakness.</i>

92
00:07:12,641 --> 00:07:17,481
<i>The rain fulfilled that need,</i>
<i>but also fulfilled a more practical need:</i>

93
00:07:17,562 --> 00:07:20,022
<i>we are in a theater</i>
<i>that does not have wings,</i>

94
00:07:20,106 --> 00:07:21,476
<i>does not have a fly tower.</i>

95
00:07:21,566 --> 00:07:23,526
<i>How do we change the scenery?</i>

96
00:07:26,363 --> 00:07:30,453
<i>We are using our rain box</i>
<i>like a curtain, practically.</i>

97
00:07:31,409 --> 00:07:33,239
<i>From the actors' point of view,</i>

98
00:07:33,328 --> 00:07:36,408
<i>they enjoy the way that they are</i>
<i>revealed and concealed</i>

99
00:07:36,498 --> 00:07:39,208
<i>at the beginning and the end</i>
<i>of each of their monologues.</i>

100
00:07:40,377 --> 00:07:46,587
This is a theater which has a brick wall
right behind what you see there,

101
00:07:46,675 --> 00:07:50,345
and the audience who come to this space
know that brick wall intimately,

102
00:07:50,428 --> 00:07:54,928
they're used to being confronted
with shallow space.

103
00:07:57,352 --> 00:08:00,902
<i>So to give them depth</i>
<i>and an element that is real.</i>

104
00:08:01,773 --> 00:08:07,533
<i>You can feel the audience feeling</i>
<i>the emotional response that anybody has</i>

105
00:08:07,612 --> 00:08:10,162
<i>towards lit rain in a small, dark room.</i>

106
00:08:11,658 --> 00:08:13,408
<i>And I'm satisfied.</i>

107
00:08:16,538 --> 00:08:18,958
<i>By the way,</i>
<i>I have no idea how the rain system works.</i>

108
00:08:19,040 --> 00:08:21,170
<i>It just shows</i>
<i>that you can design nice things</i>

109
00:08:21,251 --> 00:08:23,041
<i>without having a clue</i>
<i>how they fucking work.</i>

110
00:08:25,005 --> 00:08:30,215
Es is somebody who absolutely
amazes me every time we work.

111
00:08:30,301 --> 00:08:32,891
<i>I come back excited from meetings,</i>

112
00:08:32,971 --> 00:08:38,311
because she's always coming up
with information I would've never known

113
00:08:38,393 --> 00:08:42,193
or discovered by any other means.

114
00:08:42,272 --> 00:08:46,032
<i>A new stimulus every time,</i>
<i>many in a meeting.</i>

115
00:08:48,069 --> 00:08:50,859
[Es]<i> Normally, throughout the process</i>
<i>there will be a number of meetings.</i>

116
00:08:50,947 --> 00:08:53,157
<i>There might be five or there might be 25.</i>

117
00:08:53,742 --> 00:08:56,662
<i>And it might take a year</i>
<i>or three years or three months.</i>

118
00:08:58,038 --> 00:09:00,368
<i>I will have my team make models.</i>

119
00:09:00,457 --> 00:09:02,997
I will draw the kind of models
I think it's going to be,

120
00:09:03,084 --> 00:09:06,424
and then when I come back,
we've got a whole bunch of options.

121
00:09:06,504 --> 00:09:09,134
<i>Sometimes they're interesting.</i>
<i>Sometimes they're less interesting.</i>

122
00:09:09,215 --> 00:09:10,465
<i>We have another meeting,</i>

123
00:09:10,550 --> 00:09:12,590
we say, "We think it could be this,
it could be that..."

124
00:09:13,344 --> 00:09:16,144
<i>So you need to turn up with everything.</i>

125
00:09:17,432 --> 00:09:19,522
[upbeat music playing]

126
00:09:23,646 --> 00:09:27,526
[Es] This is actually probably
the most recent, and it's a rejected idea.

127
00:09:29,486 --> 00:09:34,816
He was drawn in Paris
in Karl Lagerfeld's studio,

128
00:09:34,908 --> 00:09:39,198
while Kanye West and Kim Kardashian
were being photographed on a bed.

129
00:09:40,997 --> 00:09:45,667
And I sat at the end of the bed
drawing ideas that Kanye was having

130
00:09:45,752 --> 00:09:50,052
and one of them was a man
made out of LED,

131
00:09:50,131 --> 00:09:53,761
<i>and this posture is the result</i>
<i>of many, many sketches.</i>

132
00:09:53,843 --> 00:09:55,893
<i>Because at first, he looked too strong,</i>

133
00:09:55,970 --> 00:09:57,850
<i>then he didn't look</i>
<i>sufficiently vulnerable.</i>

134
00:09:57,931 --> 00:10:01,681
<i>so we got to a sketch that he loved</i>
<i>on that day</i>

135
00:10:01,768 --> 00:10:02,978
and we made this model.

136
00:10:03,061 --> 00:10:07,151
And then we took it to Los Angeles
and it was hated instantly,

137
00:10:07,232 --> 00:10:08,692
so it came home in shame.

138
00:10:09,234 --> 00:10:10,904
And it's hanging its head in shame

139
00:10:10,985 --> 00:10:13,525
with a little parrot-headed man on it
to cheer it up.

140
00:10:14,405 --> 00:10:15,695
[laughs]

141
00:10:29,796 --> 00:10:31,166
-[Es] You have that...
-Mm-hmm.

142
00:10:31,256 --> 00:10:34,006
-[Es] I want a little doorway.
-Just flat?

143
00:10:34,092 --> 00:10:35,302
-Blank.
-Flush.

144
00:10:35,385 --> 00:10:36,545
-A flush door.
-Mm-hmm.

145
00:10:36,636 --> 00:10:37,676
[Es] And it can open.

146
00:10:37,762 --> 00:10:43,432
<i>I was invited to make a piece</i>
<i>for the Belgian </i>Triennale<i> Exhibition.</i>

147
00:10:44,769 --> 00:10:49,819
<i>It's an exhibition about</i>
<i>the relationship between music and art.</i>

148
00:10:49,899 --> 00:10:51,899
<i>A visual embodiment of music.</i>

149
00:10:51,985 --> 00:10:56,355
<i>And that's why I was invited to take part,</i>
<i>because of the work I've done in music.</i>

150
00:10:56,447 --> 00:10:57,987
You know what you could do?

151
00:10:58,700 --> 00:11:03,200
You could put the gauze there
and then have just a torn out area.

152
00:11:04,372 --> 00:11:06,752
So, I think that's quite elegant,
if you just stretch it.

153
00:11:06,833 --> 00:11:09,173
Yeah, I think that
would look really smart.

154
00:11:10,211 --> 00:11:13,841
<i>I immediately wanted to make</i>
<i>a cube that would revolve,</i>

155
00:11:13,923 --> 00:11:17,143
<i>that would have different apertures</i>
<i>on different sides,</i>

156
00:11:17,218 --> 00:11:21,468
<i>projecting images of some</i>
<i>of the shows I've made over 20 years.</i>

157
00:11:23,099 --> 00:11:25,179
I'll tell you
what my mind's going through:

158
00:11:25,268 --> 00:11:27,648
is whether it's interesting
to see the mess inside,

159
00:11:27,729 --> 00:11:30,439
or whether you want to keep it mysterious,
you know. That's the--

160
00:11:31,190 --> 00:11:32,400
That's the point.

161
00:11:33,610 --> 00:11:35,110
-Ta-da!
-Okay.

162
00:11:35,194 --> 00:11:38,114
[laughs] I love that, I'm going to come
around here more often. It's done!

163
00:11:39,908 --> 00:11:41,868
<i>There's an element</i>
<i>of anxiety about it all.</i>

164
00:11:42,493 --> 00:11:44,043
<i>There's an element of terror,</i>

165
00:11:44,120 --> 00:11:48,500
because Kanye is not going to be there,
Beyonc√© is not going to be there.

166
00:11:48,583 --> 00:11:53,133
I've got to make something
that is worth watching on its own,

167
00:11:53,588 --> 00:11:55,668
which I haven't really made before,
so we'll see.

168
00:11:55,757 --> 00:11:57,507
It might or might not be worth watching.

169
00:12:11,773 --> 00:12:12,823
[doorbell rings]

170
00:12:14,484 --> 00:12:15,694
<i>-</i>[intercom] <i>Hello?</i>
-[Es] Hello!

171
00:12:15,777 --> 00:12:16,987
[door buzzes]

172
00:12:18,821 --> 00:12:21,741
[Tim] <i>I would never have been seen dead</i>
<i>at a pop concert,</i>

173
00:12:23,284 --> 00:12:25,794
and I'd never would have gone to one
but for Es.

174
00:12:25,870 --> 00:12:28,410
Well, he can speak for himself.
I would've been to lots.

175
00:12:28,998 --> 00:12:30,828
But I think it's the spectacle.

176
00:12:30,917 --> 00:12:33,627
[Tim] <i>All those lights that come up,</i>
<i>people taking pictures</i>

177
00:12:33,711 --> 00:12:37,381
<i>and the deafening noise and everything,</i>
<i>I've actually quite taken to it.</i>

178
00:12:38,466 --> 00:12:41,296
This was a lovely Christmas present
Es gave us last year,

179
00:12:41,386 --> 00:12:46,716
and it's offcuts from a big set she did
in Dresden, and it's<i> Der Freisch√ºtz.</i>

180
00:12:46,808 --> 00:12:50,808
Another nice thing is we get to see
a lot of the stuff she does,

181
00:12:50,895 --> 00:12:54,975
so we're camp followers.
We are roadies, really. We go around.

182
00:12:55,066 --> 00:12:57,986
And it's wonderful, because all sorts
of places we'd never would've been.

183
00:12:58,820 --> 00:13:01,280
[Angela] <i>By the way, my husband,</i>
<i>you may not know this...</i>

184
00:13:01,364 --> 00:13:03,034
<i>Es's dad is a great crocheter.</i>

185
00:13:03,116 --> 00:13:05,276
<i>-</i>[Tim]<i> That's my speciality--</i>
<i>-</i>[Angela]<i> He makes tea cozies--</i>

186
00:13:05,368 --> 00:13:07,118
<i>-</i>[Tim] <i>I also made the table.</i>
<i>-</i>[Angela] <i>He made this table.</i>

187
00:13:07,203 --> 00:13:09,543
-My husband made this table.
-This is out of scaffolding planks.

188
00:13:09,622 --> 00:13:11,042
Yep. Old scaffolding boards.

189
00:13:11,124 --> 00:13:14,714
I mean, 90% of the stuff in this house
is from junk shops

190
00:13:14,794 --> 00:13:16,384
<i>and we just painted them or made them.</i>

191
00:13:16,462 --> 00:13:17,302
[Tim] <i>Yeah.</i>

192
00:13:17,380 --> 00:13:19,630
[Angela] <i>So I think Es has done</i>
<i>exactly the same thing,</i>

193
00:13:19,716 --> 00:13:23,966
<i>but we never really thought she'd go</i>
<i>into anything connected with art.</i>

194
00:13:24,971 --> 00:13:26,311
<i>Music was her thing.</i>

195
00:13:28,391 --> 00:13:31,311
[Es]<i> My way of escaping or adventuring</i>
<i>away from the countryside</i>

196
00:13:31,394 --> 00:13:32,524
<i>was through music.</i>

197
00:13:36,149 --> 00:13:39,439
<i>'Cause I would go up to London</i>
<i>on the train, age 11, on my own,</i>

198
00:13:41,070 --> 00:13:44,280
<i>and I had music lessons in London</i>
<i>at the Royal Academy,</i>

199
00:13:44,365 --> 00:13:46,695
<i>and then when I finished my music lessons,</i>

200
00:13:46,784 --> 00:13:48,874
<i>I would then have</i>
<i>the rest of the day in London,</i>

201
