on a piece called<i> The Nether,</i>

293
00:19:13,486 --> 00:19:18,366
<i>which was about a world created digitally.</i>

294
00:19:18,449 --> 00:19:22,909
<i>So I somehow needed to make the audience</i>
<i>not trust their environment.</i>

295
00:19:22,995 --> 00:19:25,825
<i>So what was interesting is people</i>
<i>who came out of that play</i>

296
00:19:25,915 --> 00:19:29,745
<i>described having seen a glass box,</i>
<i>but actually, there was no box.</i>

297
00:19:29,835 --> 00:19:31,625
<i>There was nothing there,</i>

298
00:19:31,712 --> 00:19:36,842
<i>it was just objects placed in space</i>
<i>with a mirror set quite far behind them,</i>

299
00:19:36,926 --> 00:19:40,216
<i>so the audience's depth perception</i>
<i>was really messed about with</i>

300
00:19:40,304 --> 00:19:42,014
<i>so they thought they were reading a box</i>

301
00:19:42,098 --> 00:19:45,518
<i>and they were just reading objects</i>
<i>in relation to an invisible box.</i>

302
00:19:46,602 --> 00:19:51,362
And I use mirror a lot in the fashion
shows I've been doing with Louis Vuitton.

303
00:19:53,484 --> 00:19:56,954
<i>This is a new discovery</i>
<i>of a transparent, two-way mirror</i>

304
00:19:57,446 --> 00:20:00,566
<i>that is mirror whenever</i>
<i>there is not light behind it.</i>

305
00:20:01,409 --> 00:20:04,999
<i>So, if you put a piece of LED screen</i>
<i>behind a piece of two-way mirror,</i>

306
00:20:05,079 --> 00:20:09,829
<i>then if you conjure a face</i>
<i>against black behind mirror,</i>

307
00:20:09,917 --> 00:20:14,257
<i>then the mirror will reflect the room</i>
<i>everywhere except where the face is,</i>

308
00:20:14,338 --> 00:20:19,548
<i>so you effectively see a suspended face</i>
<i>amidst a huge double sized room.</i>

309
00:20:21,262 --> 00:20:23,222
I'm making more immersive pieces

310
00:20:23,305 --> 00:20:25,885
that an audience can wander around
and find themselves in.

311
00:20:28,310 --> 00:20:32,360
<i>Just recently, I was invited</i>
<i>to create anything I wanted</i>

312
00:20:32,440 --> 00:20:34,900
<i>for this Chanel project.</i>

313
00:20:35,401 --> 00:20:37,741
As long as it was about scent,
it could be anything.

314
00:20:45,286 --> 00:20:47,456
<i>I came up with a mirrored maze,</i>

315
00:20:48,539 --> 00:20:50,959
<i>and it seemed to me that</i>
<i>that was a good analog</i>

316
00:20:51,041 --> 00:20:55,001
<i>for the frontal brain making</i>
<i>50,000 decisions a minute.</i>

317
00:20:57,840 --> 00:21:02,510
<i>And then suddenly allow them</i>
<i>into a room where the floor falls away</i>

318
00:21:02,595 --> 00:21:03,715
<i>and they plummet.</i>

319
00:21:03,804 --> 00:21:08,484
<i>Then you'd be creating</i>
<i>a sculptural physical analog</i>

320
00:21:08,893 --> 00:21:13,443
<i>for how it feels to be</i>
<i>plummeted back in time to a memory,</i>

321
00:21:13,522 --> 00:21:16,942
<i>in the way that you do when you</i>
<i>suddenly smell your mother's perfume.</i>

322
00:21:20,488 --> 00:21:22,488
[piano music playing]

323
00:21:38,672 --> 00:21:40,512
[Es]<i> I used to come to this church</i>

324
00:21:40,591 --> 00:21:43,301
<i>and the extraordinary thing</i>
<i>about this church</i>

325
00:21:43,385 --> 00:21:47,135
<i>is it's a very small, little parish.</i>

326
00:21:49,558 --> 00:21:53,148
<i>And yet, there are</i>
<i>11 stained glass windows here,</i>

327
00:21:53,229 --> 00:21:55,559
<i>which were designed by Marc Chagall.</i>

328
00:21:56,398 --> 00:21:58,318
<i>Which is an extraordinary thing, I think.</i>

329
00:21:58,400 --> 00:22:00,490
[piano playing continues]

330
00:22:08,702 --> 00:22:11,252
[Es] <i>A local member of the parish council,</i>

331
00:22:11,330 --> 00:22:16,460
<i>his daughter died in a sailing accident</i>
<i>tragically in 1963.</i>

332
00:22:16,544 --> 00:22:17,594
<i>She was 21.</i>

333
00:22:20,172 --> 00:22:24,802
<i>In memory of her,</i>
<i>he commissioned these windows.</i>

334
00:22:24,885 --> 00:22:29,345
When Chagall came here
and saw this window in situ,

335
00:22:29,431 --> 00:22:32,981
he said, "Okay, I need to do
the whole church."

336
00:22:33,060 --> 00:22:39,230
So over the next ten years, he created
the rest of the windows, one by one.

337
00:22:39,733 --> 00:22:41,863
[piano playing continues]

338
00:22:45,030 --> 00:22:48,330
<i>There was a big Chagall exhibition</i>
<i>in the early '80s,</i>

339
00:22:48,409 --> 00:22:52,909
<i>and it would've been around that time</i>
<i>I would've seen all of Chagall's work...</i>

340
00:22:53,872 --> 00:22:56,502
<i>and also joined it together</i>
<i>with seeing these windows.</i>

341
00:22:57,167 --> 00:23:01,877
<i>So this feels like</i>
<i>paint turned into light.</i>

342
00:23:02,715 --> 00:23:06,925
The intensity of that cobalt
and ultramarine and cyan,

343
00:23:07,011 --> 00:23:10,181
all those different blues
